true, "other": "explicitly unresolved; aqueous prebiotic plausibility remains unproven"}, "mechanism": "A small chiral imbalance is amplified or selected from a racemic proline pool through eutectic partitioning, mineral adsorption, or feedback chemistry, yielding an L-enriched fraction.", "reasoning": "No established prebiotic synthesis in the provided literature yields enantiopure L-proline directly; abiotic proline is generally racemic and racemizes readily. This node is therefore explicitly speculative and included only because the requested target is L-proline. It is grounded in the documented possibilities of crystal-solution eutectic amplification for proline, CPL-induced small ee values, and proline-mediated asymmetric feedback, while acknowledging that aqueous prebiotic realization is unresolved (Hayashi et al., 2006; Klussmann et al., 2006; Bailey et al., 1998; Meinert et al., 2014; Meinert et al., 2022; List et al., 2000; Mathew et al., 2004)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Cyanosulfidic full movement-c route", "description": "The strongest literature-supported route to a direct proline precursor: HCN/H2S photochemistry in shallow anoxic pools generates a 4-carbon cyanohydrin, cyclic alpha-hydroxythioamide, gamma-butyrothiolactam, proline aminonitrile, then hydrolysis yields racemic proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic thiolactam-centered route", "description": "A shorter view of the Patel branch beginning from the cyclic alpha-hydroxythioamide and emphasizing gamma-butyrothiolactam as the decisive ring-bearing intermediate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal glutamate-family route from alpha-